  "prompt": "Why hollow shaft can transmit more torque than solid shaft?",
  "response": "A hollow shaft can often transmit more torque than a solid shaft of the same weight. The key reasons for this are related to the distribution of material and the geometry of the shaft:\n\n1. **Moment of Inertia**: In torsion, the ability of a shaft to resist twisting is determined by its polar moment of inertia. For a hollow shaft, more material is distributed further away from the center axis, which increases the polar moment of inertia. The polar moment of inertia \\(J\\) for a hollow circular shaft is given by:\n   \\[\n   J = \\frac{\\pi(d_o^4 - d_i^4)}{32}\n   \\]\n   where \\(d_o\\) is the outer diameter and \\(d_i\\) is the inner diameter. This is greater than for a solid shaft, where:\n   \\[\n   J = \\frac{\\pi d^4}{32}\n   \\]\n   for a diameter \\(d\\).\n\n2. **Weight Reduction**: For the same weight, a hollow shaft can have a larger diameter than a solid shaft, because the inside material is removed. This larger diameter increases the polar moment of inertia even though the overall weight remains the same or is reduced.\n\n3. **Strength-to-Weight Ratio**: Hollow shafts have a better strength-to-weight ratio because they efficiently use material to resist torsion. This design allows for greater torque transmission compared to a solid shaft of the same material and weight.\n\n4. **Stiffness**: Stiffness in torsion is also increased for the reasons mentioned above. A hollow shaft's larger diameter increases its ability to resist deformation under load.\n\nIn summary, a hollow shaft is more efficient in distributing material to resist torsion, leading to higher torque transmission capacity for the same weight or even less weight compared to a solid shaft. This makes hollow shafts preferable in many applications where strength and weight are critical considerations.",
